{"cursor":"24481","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\nIn electromagnetism, 'absolute permittivity' is the measure of the resistance\nthat is encountered when forming an electric field in a medium. In other words,\npermittivity is a measure of how an electric field affects, and is affected by,\na dielectric medium. The permittivity of a medium describes how much electric\nfield (more correctly, flux) is 'generated' per unit charge in that medium. More\nelectric flux exists in a medium with a high permittivity (per unit charge)\nbecause of polarization effects. Permittivity is directly related to electric\nsusceptibility, which is a measure of how easily a dielectric polarizes in\nresponse to an electric field. Thus, permittivity relates to a material's\nability to transmit (or \"permit\") an electric field.\n\nIn SI units, permittivity Îµ is measured in farads per meter (F/m); electric\nsusceptibility Ï is dimensionless. They are related to each other through\n: \\varepsilon = \\varepsilon_{\\text{r}} \\varepsilon_0 =\n:(1+\\chi)\\varepsilon_0 \nwhere Îµ r is the relative permittivity of the material, and\nÎµ 0 = 8.854187817.. Ã 10 â12 F/m is the vacuum permittivity.\n","linknr":344,"url":"Permittivity","recorded":1362485747,"links":45,"instances":["physics","electrostatics","electromagnetic_radiation","optics","electromagnetism"],"pdf":["http://physics.nist.gov/Pubs/SP330/sp330.pdf","http://falsecolour.com/aw/eps_plots/eps_plots.pdf"],"categories":["Condensed matter physics","Electric and magnetic fields in matter","Physical quantities","Concepts in physics"],"headings":["Explanation","Vacuum permittivity","Relative permittivity","Dispersion and causality","Measurement","See also","References","Further reading","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f1/Diel.gif/220px-Diel.gif","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf9/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/f/3/6/f362c9ccf087dbe83cc0